{"add":{"doc":{"id":"048d301327a344801eb2a838aa8614c6565aad896ad5a07112fdccd340ce4b97","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Ant%C3%B4nio_Parreiras_-_Pris%C3%A3o_de_Tiradentes%2C_1914.jpg/220px-Ant%C3%B4nio_Parreiras_-_Pris%C3%A3o_de_Tiradentes%2C_1914.jpg","previous":["However, the decentralized and unorganized tendencies of the captaincy colonies proved problematic, and in 1549 the Portuguese king restructured them into the Governorate General of Brazil, a single and centralized Portuguese colony in South America.[43][44] In the first two centuries of colonization, Indigenous and Europeans groups lived in constant war, establishing opportunistic alliances in order to gain advantages against each other.[45][46][47][48] By the mid-16th century, cane sugar had become Brazil's most important exportation product,[41][49] and slaves purchased in Sub-Saharan Africa, in the slave market of Western Africa[50] (not only those from Portuguese allies of their colonies in Angola and Mozambique), had become its largest import,[51][52] to cope with plantations of sugarcane, due to increasing international demand for Brazilian sugar.[53][54]"],"after":["By the end of the 17th century, sugarcane exports began to decline,[55] and the discovery of gold by bandeirantes in the 1690s would become the new backbone of the colony's economy, fostering a Brazilian Gold Rush,[56] attracting thousands of new settlers to Brazil, from Portugal and all Portuguese colonies around the World,[57] which in turn caused some conflicts between newcomers and old settlers.[58]"]}}}